node.text:
#ArrecifeAlacranes is home to turtles, sharks, corals and hundreds of other species that need protection. Science is the best tool to take care of the wealth of our seas.
.
Over the next two weeks, 10 scientists with different specialties will explore the area with Oceana and our expedition partner @Blancpain1735. They’ll complete environmental DNA analysis and photomosaic modeling, which will be used to create 3D maps of the reefs and enable a census of the species that inhabit them or use the area as part of their migratory routes.
.
Keep an eye on our feeds and stories for updates on this adventure and follow @oceanamexico for live updates (en español).
.
#Blancpain1735 #BlancpainOceanCommitment #BlancpainFiftyFathoms #FiftyFathoms #ArrecifeAlacranes

node.text:
If we protect and restore our oceans from threats like illegal and irresponsible fishing, they can feed ONE BILLION people a healthy seafood meal each day.
.
Wild fish is a healthy source of protein that doesn’t require fresh water or arable land, produces little carbon dioxide, and costs less per pound than beef, chicken, lamb or pork.
.
Sustainable fishery management can help increase the global fish catch by up to 15% from current levels. Oceana campaigns worldwide to win policy victories that protect our oceans and deliver more seafood to the future. #SaveTheOceansFeedTheWorld

node.title: Save the Oceans, Feed the World

node.text:
We must act together to stop destroying the very planet that sustains us. Join @Oceana, @oak_foundation and the hundreds of organizations that have already signed on to #RiseUp4theOcean.
.
We need to RISE UP together to:
- Restore ocean life
- Invest immediately in a net-zero carbon emissions future
- Speed the transition to a circular and sustainable economy
- Empower and support coastal people
- Unite for stronger global ocean governance
- Protect at least 30% of the ocean by 2030
.
Learn more at RISEUPfortheocean.org
.
#SaveOurOcean #Ocean #SDG14 #OceanClimateAction

node.text:
Actor, singer, author and producer @jennaushkowitz knows how important sharks are to our oceans. "Sharks are so vital to the ecosystem. They're at the top of the food chain and regulate the first population. And without them, we'd be in real danger."
.
Fins from up to 73 million sharks end up in the global shark fin trade every year. Shark finning is the practice of cutting off a shark's fin, and then often discarding the shark back into the ocean where it drowns. Sharks need your help.
.
That's why we're working with @knockaround to help protect sharks and our oceans. $5 from every pair of @sharkweek Fort Knocks sunglasses will be donated to Oceana. Get your pair from @knockaround and follow the link in our bio to tell Congress to ban the sale of shark fins in the U.S. #FinBanNow
.
#shark #sharks #sharkfinning #glee #ocean #oceans #fish #marinelife #sea #conservation

node.title: Something We Can All Agree On

node.text: TAKE ACTION: Bold legislation introduced in July would reauthorize the Magnuson-Stevens Fishery Conservation and Management Act, the landmark U.S. fisheries law. If passed, this much anticipated legislation would update our current fisheries management system to lessen the effects of climate change, reduce bycatch, rebuild fish stocks, improve collection and use of data, and promote healthy habitat for our fish. Add your name to tell your members of Congress that renewing this law is vital to the health of our fisheries and coastal communities. Link in bio. #KeepOceansFishy 🐟

node.text:
Sharks have played a vital role in maintaining healthy oceans for hundreds of millions of years as a top predator, but now this stability is in danger due to the inhumane and wasteful practice of shark finning. This gruesome practice involves chopping off a shark’s fins and dumping the body back into the ocean to slowly die. While shark finning is illegal in the U.S., the global demand for fins drives this horrible practice, and the U.S. participates in this demand by allowing the buying and selling of shark fins. Our oceans NEED sharks. Tell your members in Congress it's time to ban the sale of shark fin products in the U.S. Link in bio. #FinBanNow
.
📸: Ethan Daniels / Shutterstock

Whale, hello! 🐳
.
Humpback whales can be found all over the world, living from Antarctica to the Arctic and from the coast to the open ocean. These whales can live up to 90 years old! Many humpback whale populations have recovered thanks to protections like those Oceana campaigns for. Learn more about whales and how you can help protect them with our Marine Life Encyclopedia. Link in bio.
.

.

URGENT: Southern Resident orcas need our support. 💙 
.
These orcas are starving to death from a lack of their primary food source, Chinook salmon. Reducing fishing pressure and protecting the orca’s feeding hotspots will mean more salmon for orcas. Support urgent action to save these starving orcas now. Link in bio.
.

The theme of this year's #CleanAirDay is “Healthy Air, Healthy Planet.” 🌎 Аir pollution is not only a serious health risk, but also impacts our planet's changing climate. 
.
Oceana is campaigning to stop new offshore oil drilling and promote more planet-friendly alternatives to dirty fossil fuels, the world's leading source of carbon pollution. Add your name to help permanently protect U.S. coasts against dirty offshore drilling and take action against climate change to protect our ocean and coasts! Link in bio. 
.
#HealthyAirHealthyPlanet #ClimateChange #Pollution #ProtectOurCoast #FossilFuels #ClimateCrisis
.

Tell your members of Congress to protect and restore the health of American fisheries and coastal communities by strengthening this landmark law. Link in bio. #KeepOceansFishy

node.text: HEARTBREAKING: Mile-long swordfish drift gillnets entangle, injure, and kill ocean animals, including dolphins and critically endangered leatherback sea turtles. It's time these “walls of death” are eliminated from all U.S. waters for good. Add your name to tell representatives in U.S. Congress to support legislation to end the use of large mesh drift gillnets and protect at-risk species from being killed. Link in bio.
